[1] Costa Rica
Date: 8 Dec 2005
From: Alfonso J. Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Yahoo Noticias, Mexico, 8 Dec 2005 [trans. Mod.JGM; edited]
<http://mx.news.yahoo.com/051208/8/1kh3u.html>

The record increase in dengue fever cases in 2005 was associated with heavy
rainfalls, Dr. Maria del Rocio Saenz, Costa Rica Health Minister, explained
last Thursday.
Other reasons stated by the officer were the delay in the availability of
budget resources, as well as a false sense of confidence because of the
drop in the frequency of the disease in 2004.
"Last year we had 9000 cases, it was a huge success, but we relaxed ...
last Tuesday we reported 35 700 patients, and 51 of them had dengue
hemorrhagic fever", pointed out Dr. Saenz in a press conference at which
she presented her office's annual report. She reminded the audience that
only 2 patients died.
--
