[3] India
Date: Tue, 6 Dec 2005 05:50:29 -0500 (EST)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Delhi Newsline, India, 5 Dec 2005 [edited]
<http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=160250>

With 3 new cases of dengue reported today, the total number of cases in the
city is now 1005. The Health Department of the Municipal Corporation of
Delhi (MCD) had predicted the figure to reach 1200 by this time.
Health experts and MCD officials said the drop in temperature has resulted
in the end of the dengue outbreak. ''Mosquitoes that spread dengue stop
multiplying at low temperatures," said Dr N.P. Singh, Professor of
Medicine, Maulana Azad Medical College.
He says the lowest temperature at which these mosquitoes can survive is
about 15 degrees [Centigrade]. ''The few cases that are being reported now
are isolated ones. The decreasing number of cases indicate that the dengue
virus is on the decline,'' says Singh.
Municipal Health Officer Dr K.N. Tewari also said the number of cases has
gone down with the change in the weather. ''But until cases [stop] coming
from other states, we will not be able to control the disease,'' he said,
adding that an average of 2-3 cases from other states are reported
everyday. Of the 1005 cases reported from hospitals around the city, 360
are from other states. And of the 9 reported deaths, 5 are from other states.
According to Tewari, dengue outbreaks are periodic, i.e. they usually occur
every few years. The last outbreak happened in 2003, when 2843 cases and 34
deaths were reported. ''However, sometimes one peak is followed by another
the next year, as happened in Thailand,'' warns Tewari.
To prevent an outbreak next year [2006], says Tewari, precautions should be
taken starting in January or February. He says people need to make sure
their overhead tanks are completely sealed, even buy new lids if necessary,
to make sure mosquitoes do not breed.
''Though we carry out anti-dengue operations, no agency alone can stop the
spread of the disease. It has to be an initiative on the part of the people
as well,'' said Tewari.
--
