[4] Sri Lanka (Colombo)
Date: Wed, 7 Dec 2005 12:12:40 -0500 (EST)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Webindia123, India, 7 Dec 2005 [edited]
<http://news.webindia123.com/news/showdetails.asp?id=184252&n_date=20051207&cat=Health>

Sri Lanka has reported an increase in the number of people affected by
dengue over the last few days following torrential rains and floods in many
parts of the country, Daily News reported Wednesday.
The dengue cases have increased to 67, health authorities said. The highest
number of dengue cases was reported from Colombo, followed by Matara. Cases
of dengue were also reported from Badulla, Kurunegala and Puttalam.
The healthcare and nutrition ministry said an integrated programme has been
launched to combat the spread of the diseases in flood-affected areas. The
ministry asked people to clean their wells after the floods recede.
The ministry also warned that water accumulation in pools may cause the
spread of mosquito-borne diseases such as dengue and [filariasis] and
requested people to ensure that pools of water are drained. [A similar
report was brought to ProMED's attention by Dr. Alfonso J. Rodriguez]
--
