[6] Venezuela
Date: 6 Dec 2005
From: Alfonso J. Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: El Universal, Caracas, Venezuela. 06 Dec2005 [trans. Mod.JGM; edited]
<http://politica.eluniversal.com/2005/12/06/ccs_art_06403E.shtml>

Recent reports from the Municipal Epidemiology Service (MES) show a
reduction in the number of dengue fever cases in Libertador municipality;
however, epidemiologists do not consider that these figures definitive, [as
judged by] environmental parameters, such as rainfall, garbage, and debris
in some areas of the city. Dr. Lisbeth Suarez, a local epidemiologist
working at the MES, indicated that the parishes with the highest incidence
of dengue fever are Sucre, Antimano, La Vega, San Juan, and Santa Rosalia.
During the last epidemiological week in which official data had been
registered [week No. 47] (20-26 Nov), in which 95 dengue fever cases were
reported, 70 were classical and 20 were dengue hemorrhagic fever. Dr.
Suarez announced that fumigation and abate spraying have been performed in
areas most affected by dengue fever, e.g., El Cementerio and the
communities of Los Sin Techo and El Leon in Santa Rosalia parish. Dr.
Suarez stated that during November 2005 there was a reduction in the number
of dengue fever cases compared to 130 and 140 cases of dengue fever, which
[were commonly reported] in September and October, but she also said that
"this is not a successful situation".
According to the Epidemiological Bulletin from the Ministry of Health, in
Epidemiological Week No. 46 (13-19 Nov), 838 dengue fever cases were
diagnosed in Venezuela, 62 (7.4 percent) of them were dengue hemorrhagic
fever, and 776 were classical dengue fever.
As of the aforementioned report, there have been 37 684 dengue fever cases,
2370 corresponding to dengue hemorrhagic fever (6.3 percent) and the
remaining (35 314) classical dengue fever.
The cumulated case toll up to the 46th Epidemiological Week showed a 36.3
percent increase compared to registered cases during [2004]. In this last
week no deaths caused by this viral disease have been reported.
The Epidemiological Bulletin from the Ministry of Health indicates that
persons less than 15 years old are those most affected by dengue fever
(53.1 percent of all notified cases).
Libertador municipality is the area that had the highest case number (82),
followed by Miranda state (80), Barinas (78), Merida (72), Lara (62),
Tachira (62), Falcon (60); and Aragua (52).
Epidemiological Bulletin from the Ministry of Health considers this an
epidemic. Local and regional sanitary authorities, as well as the general
population, must take preventive measures.
