[9] Yemen
Date: Thu, 1 Dec 2005 09:48:36 -0500 (EST)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Yemen Times, Yemen, 1st Dec 2005 [edited]
<http://yementimes.com/article.shtml?i=899&p=health&a=3>

A Parliament report revealed that 1000 dengue infections were registered in
Shabowa governate (458 km southeast of Sana'a) as of 8 Jun 2005. The report
warned that dengue fever will spread to all provinces of the governate if
measures are not taken.
The report mentioned that current efforts to fight this disease are
insufficient in terms of technical, financial, and human resources. The
report asked the ministry to evaluate the situation by sending field teams
to all the governorates of Yemen.
Dengue fever is a treatable infectious disease carried by mosquitoes and is
found mostly during and shortly after the rainy season in tropical and
subtropical areas. Dengue can be caused by any one of 4 types of the dengue
virus: DEN-1, DEN-2, DEN-3, and DEN-4. A person can be infected by at least
2, if not all 4 types at different times during a life span, but only once
by [each] type.
Since dengue fever was first detected on 16 Dec [what year?] in the small
city of Zabid in Hudaidah, 124 cases of infection have been reported. By
mid-January 7 people in the city had died of the disease, the ministry
report said.
Dr. Hashim Elzein, WHO representative in Yemen, said that type 1 was
discovered for the first time in some districts of Shabwa province in July
2002, then appeared again in 2003 in Ataq city, the capital of Shabwa province.
"The results from the laboratories showed that people from whom blood was
collected in Hudaidah and Zabid, as well as those from Shabwa, were exposed
to dengue fever before 2002," he explained.
The danger of dengue fever depends on its type, the doctor explained: "We
have to differentiate between dengue fever and dengue hemorrhagic fever.
Dengue fever is usually without bleeding, but dengue hemorrhagic fever
causes hemorrhaging, and people can bleed from the gums, the intestines,
stomach or from the nose, as well as having other symptoms," Dr. Alzein said.
--
