[10] Peru (Lima)
Date: Thu, 01 Dec 2005 09:45:20 +0100
From: Jorge Gonzalez <jgonzale@ins.gob.pe>
Source: La Ultima, noticias, Peru, 30 Nov 2005 [trans. Mod.JGM; edited]
<http://www.laultima.com/noticia.php?id=14867&seccion=Nacional&idcategoria=4>

The Peruvian Ministry of Health (MINSA) has issued an alert. After an
exhaustive study performed in Lima, MINSA announced that the presence of
_Aedes aegypti_, the vector for dengue fever, has been detected in 112
areas in Lima (19 districts). They warn that there is a high risk for new
outbreaks of the disease this summer (mid-December to mid-April).
Even though municipalities are working alongside health authorities to
prevent dengue from developing within their area, there are problems that
will not be solved in time.
National Coordinator for the Sanitary Strategy Against Vector-Borne
Diseases at MINSA, Dr. Luis Miguel Leon, explained that the lack of
drinkable water is the main problem in the fight against dengue fever.
According to experts, it is a very difficult problem to be solved in 2 months.
"Finding one mosquito is enough reason to be worried about health in the
district. This is of more concern in areas that had already been affected
by this virus in the past", he informed.
Dr. Leon also called attention to the increasing risk that the possibility
lethal dengue hemorrhagic fever may develop in Comas.
According to MINSA reports, during 2005, 1200 dengue fever cases were
detected in La Libertad area in Comas District. Dr. Leon says that the
actual number of cases must be higher than the figures reported.
"A 2nd exposure to the virus increases the likelihood for developing
hemorrhagic dengue fever, and the epidemics may get complicated", he added.
Comas District Mayor, Mr. Julio Saldana, said that he is aware of the risk
for his community, since it is an area that has already been affected by
the virus. He announced that for this reason, prevention activities have
been carried out during the last few months in Comas neighborhoods.
"The 1st thing we did is to establish the 'Health [Round] Table,'
consisting of healthcare networks, the citizens, and the municipality", he
informed.
Major Saldana emphasized the importance of educating the population about
the actions necessary for preventing dengue fever. "We initiated an intense
campaign in coordination with health authorities so that the population may
learn what facilitates the growth of mosquito larvae."
Lack of drinkable water in the poorest areas in Lima makes them vulnerable
to the reproduction of the mosquito that is the vector for dengue. "Saving
water in receptacles outside houses and without any sanitary measures is a
risk for neighbours", said Dr. Leon.
In Comas, one of the most vulnerable areas, a new prevention system had
been implemented, using of larvicidal compounds.
Mr. Saldana also announced that bags containing larvicidal compound are
being given out to the residents of the most risky areas. "The bags'
contents are to be dissolved in the water container; it kills any mosquito
larvae. The effect lasts up to 15 days", he indicated.
Dr. Leon said that even though no cases have yet been reported yet, there
is a high risk.
[Elsevier reference: Halstead SB, Heinz FX, Barrett ADT, Roehrig JT.
Conference report: dengue virus: molecular basis of cell entry and
pathogenesis, 25-27 Jun 2003, Vienna, Austria. Vaccine 2005; 23(7): 849-56.
